    <stitle>STARTING MOTORS - PINION CLEARANCE - 42-MT AND 50-MT</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="check" graphiccount="2">
        <title>42-MT AND 50-MT</title>
        <para>To check pinion or drive clearance follow the steps listed below.</para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Make connections as shown in
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0803622">Figure 22</hotlnk>.
            </para>
            <figure id="f0803622" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0803622" filename="../figg08/G0803622.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Connections for Checking Pinion Clearance, 42-MT</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Momentarily flash a jumper lead from ground return terminal to terminal "M". The drive will
                now shift into cranking position and remain so until the battery is disconnected.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Push the pinion or drive back towards the commutator end to eliminate slack movement.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Measure the distance between drive and housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0803623">Figure 23</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f0803623" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0803623" filename="../figg08/G0803623.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Checking Pinion Clearance, 42MT and 52 MT</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. PLUG REMOVED</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. SHAFT NUT</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. PRESS ON DRIVE TO TAKE UP MOVEMENT</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. PINION</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. .330 TO .390-INCH PINION CLEARANCE</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Adjust clearance by removing plug and turning shaft nut. Although typical specifications are
                shown, always refer to specifications applying to the specific models.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
